Image references, and tagging in practice.

Recall the reference grammar from module two: optionally a registry host and port, optionally a namespace, then the repository, optionally a tag, and optionally a digest. Now let's fill in what each piece controls. The registry host defaults to docker dot i-o, and determines which registry's a-p-i to hit. The namespace defaults to library on Hub, and says which user or organisation owns it. The repository is required, and is the image's name. The tag defaults to latest, and points at whichever manifest the registry has right now; it's mutable. And the digest, written with an at-sign and a hash, names a specific manifest; it's immutable, and it wins over the tag if both are present.

Tag plus digest together is the production pattern: the tag for humans, the digest for certainty. Something like my-app, tag one point four point two, at s-h-a two fifty-six, reads clearly and resolves to exact bytes.

Now, tagging in practice. In a real organisation, continuous integration tags one freshly-built image several ways at once: the git hash, a semantic version if the commit is a release, and a channel name, like main or r-c. All of them point at the same manifest digest, so pushing all of them costs one upload. And at deploy time, the deploy manifest references the image by digest, or by an immutable semantic version, for reproducibility.

Is tag latest ever okay? Three answers. For images you publish, almost never, because downstream users get a moving target. For images you consume locally, it's fine; docker run n-ginx saves typing. And for production deploys, never; a docker pull six months from now won't necessarily get the image you tested. Some registries enforce this with tag immutability, like e-c-r's immutable tags, or Harbor's immutable repositories; turn it on for release tags, so a one point four point two can never be silently re-pointed. The rule: name for humans with tags, and deploy for certainty with digests.
